00:01:41.560 --> 00:01:45.080
But it's very important
here is that we are not

00:01:45.080 --> 00:01:47.770
keeping track of what
happens in the environment,

00:01:47.770 --> 00:01:51.140
and that's associated here with
a little bucket or trash can.

00:01:51.140 --> 00:01:54.350
Every result photons
or such are measured,

00:01:54.350 --> 00:01:59.040
the environment is constantly
projected on a measurement

00:01:59.040 --> 00:02:03.200
basis, and therefore,
re-introduce probabilistic

00:02:03.200 --> 00:02:07.970
element into the part
we don't observe mainly

00:02:07.970 --> 00:02:12.470
the part which
characterizes the atoms.

00:02:12.470 --> 00:02:19.690
So for that we need the
formalism of density matrix,

00:02:19.690 --> 00:02:26.065
and that's where
we want to start.

00:02:29.850 --> 00:02:34.540
At the end of last
lecture, I reminded you

00:02:34.540 --> 00:02:36.880
that the density
matrix can always

00:02:36.880 --> 00:02:39.700
be written as an
ensemble where you

00:02:39.700 --> 00:02:42.520
say you have a certain
probability for certain rate

00:02:42.520 --> 00:02:45.160
function.

00:02:45.160 --> 00:02:48.660
This is always possible,
but it is not unique.

00:02:48.660 --> 00:02:52.580
So each of you could actually
create the same density matrix

00:02:52.580 --> 00:02:55.460
by preparing a number
of quantum states

00:02:55.460 --> 00:02:57.420
with a certain
probability and saying

00:02:57.420 --> 00:02:58.960
this is my density matrix.

00:02:58.960 --> 00:03:01.700
And also each of you has
prepared different quantum

00:03:01.700 --> 00:03:02.630
states.

00:03:02.630 --> 00:03:04.640
If you sum them up
in that same way,

00:03:04.640 --> 00:03:09.280
you get the same density matrix
and therefore, all observables

00:03:09.280 --> 00:03:12.280
or measurements you will do
on your ensemble in the future

00:03:12.280 --> 00:03:15.320
will be identical because
the density matrix is

00:03:15.320 --> 00:03:17.890
a full description
of the system.

00:03:17.890 --> 00:03:20.705
So at that level, it may
look sort of very trivial

00:03:20.705 --> 00:03:23.000
that we have
different unraveling.

00:03:23.000 --> 00:03:25.130
Unraveling means you
look microscopically

00:03:25.130 --> 00:03:27.140
what is behind the
density matrix,

00:03:27.140 --> 00:03:28.640
but in your homework
assignment, you

00:03:28.640 --> 00:03:32.970
will all show that you can have
a system which have very, very

00:03:32.970 --> 00:03:34.990
different dissipation
mechanisms,

00:03:34.990 --> 00:03:37.290
but they're described
by the same equation.

00:03:37.290 --> 00:03:41.490
So therefore, it's
physically not possible

00:03:41.490 --> 00:03:45.280
to distinguish by just measuring
the density matrix what

00:03:45.280 --> 00:03:46.810
causes a dissipation.

00:03:46.810 --> 00:03:49.400
Of course, if you know
what causes a dissipation,

00:03:49.400 --> 00:03:50.990
fluctuating fields
or collisions,

00:03:50.990 --> 00:03:53.630
you know more than the
density matrix knows.

