00:09:24.220 --> 00:09:27.400
But the other one which
is often not so explicit.

00:09:27.400 --> 00:09:29.860
If you send your
photons away, you're

00:09:29.860 --> 00:09:31.800
not keeping track
of what happens,

00:09:31.800 --> 00:09:34.510
but you could as well
perform a measurement,

00:09:34.510 --> 00:09:36.360
and this is what we put in here.

00:09:36.360 --> 00:09:42.630
We say those photons
hit a bucket or detector

00:09:42.630 --> 00:09:44.300
and measure them,
we observe them.

00:09:44.300 --> 00:09:46.140
There's nothing else
we do with them,

00:09:46.140 --> 00:09:49.040
so we can as well measure them,
and this being immediately

00:09:49.040 --> 00:09:53.281
lead to the equation
for the density matrix.

00:09:53.281 --> 00:09:54.780
So this is what you
want to discuss,

00:09:54.780 --> 00:09:56.980
and it will have all
the ingredients later

00:09:56.980 --> 00:09:59.390
on in a mathematically
simple form

00:09:59.390 --> 00:10:02.270
for the derivation
of master equation.

00:10:02.270 --> 00:10:09.170
So let's consider a
similar photon for that.

00:10:12.580 --> 00:10:16.630
So the wave function,
this is superposition

00:10:16.630 --> 00:10:20.950
of no photon and 1 photon,
and the coefficients

00:10:20.950 --> 00:10:23.930
are alpha and beta.

00:10:23.930 --> 00:10:28.630
And just for
simplifying notation,

00:10:28.630 --> 00:10:31.820
I pick alpha and
beta to be real.

00:10:31.820 --> 00:10:44.640
So what do we expect to
happen at the beam splitter?

00:10:44.640 --> 00:10:48.175
Well, there's a probability
that the photon gets reflected.

00:10:54.100 --> 00:10:58.760
Probability to
reflect the photon

00:10:58.760 --> 00:11:00.500
and therefore to
observe the photon.

00:11:06.470 --> 00:11:10.940
This probability is, of course,
beta square-- the probability

00:11:10.940 --> 00:11:15.280
that we have a photon to
begin with-- and then the beam

00:11:15.280 --> 00:11:18.560
splitter, remember we
categorized the beam

00:11:18.560 --> 00:11:21.280
splitter with angle
sine theta cosine theta.

00:11:21.280 --> 00:11:23.720
Sine theta was the
reflection amplitude,

00:11:23.720 --> 00:11:26.470
cosine theta, the
transmission amplitude.

00:11:26.470 --> 00:11:30.940
So this probability,
which I call P1

00:11:30.940 --> 00:11:37.660
is the probability for
reflection and for measurement.

00:11:37.660 --> 00:11:42.460
And now naively you
would think what

00:11:42.460 --> 00:11:45.270
happens after the system
has passed through the beam

00:11:45.270 --> 00:11:49.170
splitter, with a probability of
P1, we've measured the photon.

00:11:49.170 --> 00:11:51.980
We know for sure there
is no photon left.

00:11:51.980 --> 00:11:56.930
The system is in
the vacuum state,

00:11:56.930 --> 00:11:59.980
but then you would say,
well, maybe with probability

00:11:59.980 --> 00:12:05.030
1 minus P1, we have
not measured anything.

00:12:05.030 --> 00:12:07.480
Nothing has happened
to the wave function,

00:12:07.480 --> 00:12:09.760
and that means the wave
function just continuous.

00:12:12.570 --> 00:12:17.750
Well as we will
see, this is wrong.

00:12:17.750 --> 00:12:19.640
We are missing something.

00:12:19.640 --> 00:12:24.730
What we are actually missing
is that if you measure nothing,

00:12:24.730 --> 00:12:26.460
the wave function is not sine.

00:12:26.460 --> 00:12:29.540
The possibility that we could
have measured something,

00:12:29.540 --> 00:12:31.930
changes the wave function.

00:12:31.930 --> 00:12:36.260
I will comment on that in much
more detail in a few lectures

00:12:36.260 --> 00:12:38.290
down the road when
I derive for you

00:12:38.290 --> 00:12:40.040
quantum Monte Carlo
wave function.

00:12:40.040 --> 00:12:42.450
I will have a wonderful
discussions with you

00:12:42.450 --> 00:12:46.530
about how does non-observation
change a wave function.

00:12:46.530 --> 00:12:49.190
So we will talk about
the physics behind it

00:12:49.190 --> 00:12:50.580
in some more detail.

00:12:50.580 --> 00:12:54.150
Right now, I don't want to
get into this discussion.

