00:32:17.180 --> 00:32:23.100
So before I give you the
general derivation of the master

00:32:23.100 --> 00:32:33.490
equation, let me talk
about what we have learned

00:32:33.490 --> 00:32:41.080
from this example and what
the general procedure is.

00:32:46.620 --> 00:32:53.650
The first thing is our goal
is to find a differential

00:32:53.650 --> 00:32:58.760
equation for the density
matrix of the system.

00:32:58.760 --> 00:32:59.690
I just remember.

00:32:59.690 --> 00:33:02.940
There was one thing
I wanted to mention.

00:33:02.940 --> 00:33:05.370
In the previous derivation
with the beam splitter,

00:33:05.370 --> 00:33:09.250
I started with a purer
state, and the purer state

00:33:09.250 --> 00:33:11.930
developed into a
statistical mixture,

00:33:11.930 --> 00:33:14.350
and this statistical
mixture would then

00:33:14.350 --> 00:33:16.490
transform the next
beam splitter into

00:33:16.490 --> 00:33:18.610
another statistical mixture.

00:33:18.610 --> 00:33:21.550
I derived the differential
equation for you

00:33:21.550 --> 00:33:23.530
for the first state
from the pure state

00:33:23.530 --> 00:33:25.340
to the statistical mixture.

00:33:25.340 --> 00:33:27.210
But if you would
spend a few minutes,

00:33:27.210 --> 00:33:29.100
you could immediately
show that you

00:33:29.100 --> 00:33:31.950
can start with an
elementary density matrix,

00:33:31.950 --> 00:33:34.300
look how it evolves
through the beam splitter,

00:33:34.300 --> 00:33:38.750
and you get exactly the
same differential equation.

00:33:46.380 --> 00:33:52.260
So the general procedure is,
we want a differential equation

00:33:52.260 --> 00:33:57.490
how the density matrix
evolves with time.

00:33:57.490 --> 00:34:03.360
And this will be obtained
by finding an operator which

00:34:03.360 --> 00:34:05.925
acts on the initial
density matrix.

00:34:08.730 --> 00:34:11.949
This operator is not
a unitary operator

00:34:11.949 --> 00:34:14.100
because we are
performing measurements

00:34:14.100 --> 00:34:16.530
through the environment,
even if you don't actually

00:34:16.530 --> 00:34:17.750
perform them.

00:34:17.750 --> 00:34:20.429
Once we dump something
into the environment,

00:34:20.429 --> 00:34:22.750
it's out of our
control and anybody

00:34:22.750 --> 00:34:25.260
could go and perform
a measurement,

00:34:25.260 --> 00:34:27.330
and so we should assume
that this measurement has

00:34:27.330 --> 00:34:27.790
been taken.

00:34:27.790 --> 00:34:29.581
It's one of those
quantum mechanical things

00:34:29.581 --> 00:34:32.380
that you don't even have to
care whether somebody does it.

00:34:32.380 --> 00:34:35.790
The environment does it for you.

00:34:35.790 --> 00:34:42.699
So this operator is called
a Liouvillian operator.

00:34:45.850 --> 00:34:48.120
It's sometimes called--
and I haven't really

00:34:48.120 --> 00:34:51.389
traced down why-- it's called
sometimes super operator.

00:34:55.830 --> 00:34:57.730
I know what
superconductivity is,

00:34:57.730 --> 00:35:01.070
but I don't know what the super
powers of this operator are,

00:35:01.070 --> 00:35:06.080
but that's just a name
which you will find.

00:35:06.080 --> 00:35:08.010
The second thing
which we have used

00:35:08.010 --> 00:35:14.390
is that the evolution
of this system

00:35:14.390 --> 00:35:23.050
can be obtained from the time
evolution of the total system

00:35:23.050 --> 00:35:28.430
by performing a trace over
the degrees of freedom

00:35:28.430 --> 00:35:29.870
of the environment.

00:35:29.870 --> 00:35:31.750
This was exactly
what we actually

00:35:31.750 --> 00:35:36.070
did when we said the system
continues with probability P

00:35:36.070 --> 00:35:38.480
naught in one state
and probability

00:35:38.480 --> 00:35:39.810
P1 in the other state.

00:35:39.810 --> 00:35:42.620
The operation which lead
to this density matrix

00:35:42.620 --> 00:35:44.060
was exactly the partial trace.

00:35:49.820 --> 00:35:57.385
So this is the second
general feature

00:35:57.385 --> 00:36:00.630
which we have to implement.

00:36:00.630 --> 00:36:05.510
Thirdly, if we could
do one and two exactly,

00:36:05.510 --> 00:36:07.100
we would have an
exact formulation

00:36:07.100 --> 00:36:10.220
for a small part
of a quantum system

00:36:10.220 --> 00:36:13.030
no matter how complicated
the environment is.

00:36:13.030 --> 00:36:17.800
In practice, we can
solve the equations only

00:36:17.800 --> 00:36:22.350
when we make
simplifying assumptions

00:36:22.350 --> 00:36:23.740
about the environment.

00:36:27.870 --> 00:36:34.350
One is, it is large,
and more important,

00:36:34.350 --> 00:36:42.010
therefore, it's unchanging, and
this is the Bohr approximation.

00:36:42.010 --> 00:36:47.080
And the second feature is,
it has a short correlation

00:36:47.080 --> 00:36:55.690
time, tau c.

00:36:55.690 --> 00:36:58.160
In the beam splitter, I
have made the assumption

00:36:58.160 --> 00:37:00.490
that there is no correlation
between different beam

00:37:00.490 --> 00:37:02.460
splitters in the
derivation, which

00:37:02.460 --> 00:37:04.240
I want to walk you through.

00:37:04.240 --> 00:37:09.130
Right now, you
will see explicitly

00:37:09.130 --> 00:37:11.170
where the correlation
times enter.

00:37:11.170 --> 00:37:13.355
And this is called the
Markov approximation.

00:37:18.910 --> 00:37:26.920
And finally, this is number
four, the whole possibility

00:37:26.920 --> 00:37:33.850
to derive a master
equation hinges on the fact

00:37:33.850 --> 00:37:37.780
that we have different
time scales which

00:37:37.780 --> 00:37:39.120
are very different.

00:37:48.490 --> 00:37:58.100
We are interested in the
evolution of our system.

00:37:58.100 --> 00:38:02.680
We want to know how it relaxes,
and this is on a time scale

00:38:02.680 --> 00:38:03.700
1 over gamma.

00:38:06.240 --> 00:38:08.670
So we call this slow.

00:38:08.670 --> 00:38:13.130
We are interested
in the variation

00:38:13.130 --> 00:38:18.100
of our system, the atomic
system or the photon state,

00:38:18.100 --> 00:38:21.510
which passes through
the beam splitter,

00:38:21.510 --> 00:38:25.270
and this time scale
has to be much slower

00:38:25.270 --> 00:38:27.600
than the fluctuations
of the environment.

00:38:35.550 --> 00:38:45.440
So therefore, if the
environment has fluctuations,

00:38:45.440 --> 00:38:47.110
which in the beam
splitter model where

00:38:47.110 --> 00:38:50.510
assumed to be 0, it was
delta function of time,

00:38:50.510 --> 00:38:55.880
if that correlation time is
much smaller than the time

00:38:55.880 --> 00:39:00.480
it takes for the system
to relax and to evolve,

00:39:00.480 --> 00:39:06.300
that opens a window
delta t, and this

00:39:06.300 --> 00:39:09.370
is the time scale of
the master equation.

00:39:16.610 --> 00:39:19.650
Just to give you one example
for the spontaneous emission,

00:39:19.650 --> 00:39:22.910
the correlation
time, tau c, would

00:39:22.910 --> 00:39:27.920
be the time it takes the photon
to disappear from the atom.

00:39:27.920 --> 00:39:30.610
And the photon has
disappeared from the atom

00:39:30.610 --> 00:39:33.140
when it is one wavelengths away.

00:39:33.140 --> 00:39:35.490
So typically, the
correlation time

00:39:35.490 --> 00:39:38.330
f the vacuum for
spontaneous emission

00:39:38.330 --> 00:39:44.070
is one cycle of the
optical frequency.

00:39:44.070 --> 00:39:45.840
It's very, very fast.

00:39:45.840 --> 00:39:50.490
Whereas typical decay times
of the excited states,

00:39:50.490 --> 00:39:51.180
a nano second.

00:39:51.180 --> 00:39:53.400
It's six orders of
magnitude slower,

00:39:53.400 --> 00:39:56.160
and this is what we describe.

00:39:56.160 --> 00:39:58.892
But on a time scale
of a femtosecond

00:39:58.892 --> 00:40:04.460
of one optical cycle, the photon
has not detached from the atom

00:40:04.460 --> 00:40:06.980
and it could go actually
back to the atom.

00:40:06.980 --> 00:40:11.440
During that time, we talked
a little bit about it

00:40:11.440 --> 00:40:14.770
when we did this diagrammatic
discussions of resonance

00:40:14.770 --> 00:40:17.090
scattering for very,
very early times.

00:40:17.090 --> 00:40:21.130
You don't have exponential
decay because you cannot do

00:40:21.130 --> 00:40:24.130
the approximations where
we approximated the kernel

00:40:24.130 --> 00:40:26.860
by something which was
completely energy dependent.

00:40:26.860 --> 00:40:30.030
And so what happens
at such short times,

00:40:30.030 --> 00:40:32.994
we encounter here again
in such short times,

00:40:32.994 --> 00:40:35.160
we will not have a simple
description of the system.

00:40:47.200 --> 00:40:50.120
So the last point,
let me summarize.

00:40:50.120 --> 00:40:57.310
Our goal is that we describe the
density matrix of the system,

00:40:57.310 --> 00:41:00.420
and we want to find
the Liouville operator

00:41:00.420 --> 00:41:04.470
or some matrix which acts on it.

00:41:04.470 --> 00:41:11.490
And because we will integrate
over time steps, which

00:41:11.490 --> 00:41:14.910
are larger than the
correlation time of the system,

00:41:14.910 --> 00:41:21.520
we can also call it, it will
be a coarse-grained evolution.

00:41:28.810 --> 00:41:30.400
Any questions about that?

00:41:44.640 --> 00:41:48.550
I really like the discussion,
the derivation of the master

00:41:48.550 --> 00:41:53.490
equation, how it is presented
