00:42:37.150 --> 00:42:38.830
every technical detail.

00:42:38.830 --> 00:42:42.670
So I would really encourage
you, if there is something which

00:42:42.670 --> 00:42:45.800
piques your interest and I
hope there will be things which

00:42:45.800 --> 00:42:48.840
you'll find very interesting,
that you go to the book

00:42:48.840 --> 00:42:50.070
and read it.

00:42:50.070 --> 00:42:51.950
So I'm exactly following
that actually I

00:42:51.950 --> 00:42:53.960
used copies of the book.

00:42:53.960 --> 00:42:58.550
So we have a
Hamiltonian, which is

00:42:58.550 --> 00:43:01.730
describing the atomic system.

00:43:01.730 --> 00:43:06.521
It describes the reservoir and
then there is an interaction.

00:43:06.521 --> 00:43:09.020
We keep it very general here,
but you may always think well,

00:43:09.020 --> 00:43:13.340
the atom is your favorite
two-level system.

00:43:13.340 --> 00:43:16.350
The environment is
maybe the vacuum

00:43:16.350 --> 00:43:19.030
with all its possible
modes, and the interaction

00:43:19.030 --> 00:43:22.670
is the dipole interaction
or the a dot p interaction.

00:43:33.290 --> 00:43:41.060
So we start out
with an equation,

00:43:41.060 --> 00:43:46.630
which is nothing else
than Schrodinger's

00:43:46.630 --> 00:43:52.400
equation for the density matrix.

00:43:52.400 --> 00:43:54.360
The time derivation
of the density matrix

00:43:54.360 --> 00:43:57.670
is commutative
with the Hamilton.

00:43:57.670 --> 00:44:01.320
But it is often useful and
you've seen it many times,

00:44:01.320 --> 00:44:03.880
to go to the interaction
representation,

00:44:03.880 --> 00:44:08.370
that the time dependence
due to the unperturbed part

00:44:08.370 --> 00:44:12.810
of the operator is absorbed
in a unitary transformation,

00:44:12.810 --> 00:44:16.850
so therefore, this density
matrix in the interaction

00:44:16.850 --> 00:44:22.030
representation evolves not with,
h, because h naught is taken

00:44:22.030 --> 00:44:25.396
care of, it only involves due
to the coupling between the two

00:44:25.396 --> 00:44:27.395
systems, between the
system and the environment.

00:44:35.220 --> 00:44:38.580
So now this equation, we are
interested in a time step delta

00:44:38.580 --> 00:44:40.000
t.

00:44:40.000 --> 00:44:42.700
And this time step,
delta t remember,

00:44:42.700 --> 00:44:45.040
we want to coarse
grain, will be larger

00:44:45.040 --> 00:44:47.230
than the correlation
time of the reservoir,

00:44:47.230 --> 00:44:49.660
and you will see exactly
where it comes about.

00:44:49.660 --> 00:44:53.390
So we want to now do one of
those coarse-grain steps.

00:44:53.390 --> 00:44:57.180
We take this equation and
we integrate from time t

00:44:57.180 --> 00:44:58.580
to time t plus delta t.

00:45:01.260 --> 00:45:04.560
So this is exact here.

00:45:07.750 --> 00:45:19.815
But now we want to iterate,
and that means the following.

00:45:22.640 --> 00:45:26.750
We have expressed the time
step in the density matrix

00:45:26.750 --> 00:45:29.570
by having the
density matrix there.

00:45:29.570 --> 00:45:36.080
But now we can do in a
first-order perturbation

00:45:36.080 --> 00:45:40.260
theory, we can do one step and
we get the second order result

00:45:40.260 --> 00:45:43.640
by plugging the first order
result into this equation.

00:45:43.640 --> 00:45:46.490
It's the same we have seen
with our diagrams and such.

00:45:46.490 --> 00:45:49.950
We have an exact equation.

00:45:49.950 --> 00:45:53.090
It's useless unless we do
something, and what we do is,

00:45:53.090 --> 00:45:56.630
we realize that
we can iterate it

00:45:56.630 --> 00:46:00.630
because the part we don't
know involves one more

00:46:00.630 --> 00:46:02.840
occurrence of the
interaction potential.

00:46:02.840 --> 00:46:05.740
And when you plug the nth
order solution in here,

00:46:05.740 --> 00:46:07.647
you get the n plus
first order solution.

00:46:07.647 --> 00:46:09.230
And this is exactly
what is done here.

00:46:15.810 --> 00:46:18.370
And I skipped a
few equations here.

00:46:18.370 --> 00:46:20.990
This is what he's
done here, number one.

00:46:20.990 --> 00:46:24.160
And number two is, we are
interested in the system,

00:46:24.160 --> 00:46:26.380
not in the reservoir,
so therefore we

00:46:26.380 --> 00:46:29.910
perform the trace
over the reservoir.

00:46:29.910 --> 00:46:32.920
And the trace of the reservoir
for the photon beam splitter

00:46:32.920 --> 00:46:38.370
mend, we say we have
two possible states,

00:46:38.370 --> 00:46:40.240
we detect a photon or not.

00:46:40.240 --> 00:46:43.540
And for the system, we
have now a density matrix

00:46:43.540 --> 00:46:47.680
which is probability P naught
in one state, probability

00:46:47.680 --> 00:46:49.750
P1 in the other state.

00:46:49.750 --> 00:46:54.590
And this is exactly what the
operator partial trace does.

00:46:54.590 --> 00:46:57.030
Remember also I want
to really make sure

00:46:57.030 --> 00:46:59.190
that you recognize
all the structures.

00:46:59.190 --> 00:47:04.550
The time evolution of a density
matrix was a commutator with h,

00:47:04.550 --> 00:47:08.350
but in the interaction picture,
it's a commutator with v.

00:47:08.350 --> 00:47:13.010
But since we are putting the
first order result in here,

00:47:13.010 --> 00:47:16.610
the second order result
is now the commutator

00:47:16.610 --> 00:47:19.910
of v with the
commutator of v and o.

00:47:19.910 --> 00:47:22.430
It's just we have
iterated one more time.

00:47:30.240 --> 00:47:40.290
So the sigma tilde, the
density matrix for our system,

00:47:40.290 --> 00:47:43.470
tilde means in the
interaction picture

00:47:43.470 --> 00:47:48.180
is now the partial
trace over the reservoir

00:47:48.180 --> 00:47:50.570
of the total density matrix.

00:47:50.570 --> 00:47:52.630
Tilde means in the
interaction picture.

00:47:55.380 --> 00:48:01.840
And the important part
here is that it is exact.

00:48:01.840 --> 00:48:06.982
We have not done any
approximation here.

00:48:06.982 --> 00:48:07.565
Any questions?

00:48:24.840 --> 00:48:28.510
Of course, now we have to
make approximations because we

00:48:28.510 --> 00:48:31.870
cannot solve an interactive
problem exactly.

00:48:31.870 --> 00:48:37.080
The first one is-- and what
do we want to do in the end?

00:48:37.080 --> 00:48:41.790
We want to keep the
first non-trivial term

00:48:41.790 --> 00:48:44.910
but to the extent possible, we
want to factorize everything.

00:48:44.910 --> 00:48:47.490
We want to get rid of the
entanglement of the environment

00:48:47.490 --> 00:48:51.260
in the system and only get
sort of the minimum which

00:48:51.260 --> 00:48:53.370
is provided by the coupling.

00:48:53.370 --> 00:48:55.790
So this evolves as follows.

00:48:55.790 --> 00:49:01.640
The interaction we assume is
a product of two operators.

00:49:01.640 --> 00:49:04.380
One operator acts on
the system, one operator

00:49:04.380 --> 00:49:06.390
acts on the environment.

00:49:06.390 --> 00:49:10.115
So this could be the dipole
acting on the atom, the vacuum

00:49:10.115 --> 00:49:13.730
field, e, interacting
with the environment

00:49:13.730 --> 00:49:16.160
or it could be p dot a.

00:49:16.160 --> 00:49:20.440
Or maybe your system has
a magnetic moment, m,

00:49:20.440 --> 00:49:25.870
and the environment consists
of fluctuating magnetic fields.

00:49:25.870 --> 00:49:29.382
So we'll pretty much find
in every kind of measurement

00:49:29.382 --> 00:49:33.460
that a measurement involves
the product of two operators.

00:49:33.460 --> 00:49:36.700
One is an operator
for your system

00:49:36.700 --> 00:49:39.200
and one is an operator for the
reservoir of the environment.

00:49:44.280 --> 00:49:50.600
And so this is one
thing we want to use,

00:49:50.600 --> 00:49:53.700
and now there is one
thing which the moment we

00:49:53.700 --> 00:49:57.390
will set in our equations,
there is one thing

00:49:57.390 --> 00:50:01.560
which will naturally appear.

00:50:01.560 --> 00:50:03.414
Let me scroll back.

00:50:07.130 --> 00:50:10.520
What we have here is the
interaction operator, v,

00:50:10.520 --> 00:50:13.240
at two different times.

00:50:13.240 --> 00:50:16.410
So this means if something
happens at different times

00:50:16.410 --> 00:50:18.150
and we integrate over times.

00:50:18.150 --> 00:50:21.000
This is a correlation function,
a correlation function

00:50:21.000 --> 00:50:26.360
between v at the time t prime
and the time t double prime

00:50:26.360 --> 00:50:33.450
and since the reservoir
part of this interaction

00:50:33.450 --> 00:50:37.690
is the operator, r, so
what we have here now is,

00:50:37.690 --> 00:50:41.650
we have a correlation
between the operator, r,

00:50:41.650 --> 00:50:46.220
at two times, which
characterizes the environment.

00:50:46.220 --> 00:50:48.690
And now comes an
important approximation.

00:50:48.690 --> 00:50:54.630
You remember I said we want to
assume that the environment has

00:50:54.630 --> 00:50:56.600
a very short correlation time.

00:50:56.600 --> 00:51:01.150
Whenever a photon is emitted,
it appears dramatically fast.

00:51:01.150 --> 00:51:03.470
It disappears in
one optical cycle,

00:51:03.470 --> 00:51:05.220
and the environment
is sort of reset,

00:51:05.220 --> 00:51:07.500
it's back in the vacuum state.

00:51:07.500 --> 00:51:11.100
So this is now expressed here
that this product over which

00:51:11.100 --> 00:51:17.120
we take the partial trace has
a very short coherence time.

00:51:17.120 --> 00:51:20.900
And the fact is
now the following.

00:51:20.900 --> 00:51:29.380
We are integrating over a
coarse-grained step delta t,

00:51:29.380 --> 00:51:33.910
but this correlation function
goes to 0 in a very short time.

00:51:33.910 --> 00:51:39.810
So therefore it will
not contribute a lot.

00:51:39.810 --> 00:51:40.900
Let me write that down.

00:51:54.000 --> 00:52:00.080
What we are going to approximate
is our total density matrix

00:52:00.080 --> 00:52:08.870
is now approximately
factorizing in a density matrix

00:52:08.870 --> 00:52:11.420
describing the atomic system.

00:52:11.420 --> 00:52:14.500
Well, we describe
the atomic system

00:52:14.500 --> 00:52:17.570
when we trace out
the environment.

00:52:17.570 --> 00:52:24.190
We describe the environment when
we trace out the atomic part.

00:52:24.190 --> 00:52:26.820
And if we now form
the direct product,

00:52:26.820 --> 00:52:28.990
we are back to the
total system, but we

00:52:28.990 --> 00:52:32.500
have factorized the total
density matrix into two parts.

00:52:35.360 --> 00:52:42.140
What we neglect here is a part
which cannot be factorized

00:52:42.140 --> 00:52:44.700
which is the
correlated part of it.

00:52:47.520 --> 00:52:52.390
But what happens is, since we
are integrating over time steps

00:52:52.390 --> 00:52:55.790
delta t and the
correlation decay

00:52:55.790 --> 00:53:00.920
in a very, very short
time, the result is

00:53:00.920 --> 00:53:05.200
that this complicated part,
which we could never calculate,

00:53:05.200 --> 00:53:12.230
is smaller than the first
part by the ratio of the time

00:53:12.230 --> 00:53:16.590
where the correlations
contribute over the time delta

00:53:16.590 --> 00:53:20.100
t, the time step we
are going to take.

00:53:20.100 --> 00:53:23.720
So this is a very
critical assumption.

00:53:23.720 --> 00:53:26.900
There is a whole page
or two in the book where

00:53:26.900 --> 00:53:29.250
an photon-atom
interaction they discuss

00:53:29.250 --> 00:53:34.270
the validity of this
assumption, but I've given you

00:53:34.270 --> 00:53:38.810
the physical motivation that we
indicate over much larger time,

00:53:38.810 --> 00:53:41.330
and if this time is large
and the correlation is

00:53:41.330 --> 00:53:48.284
lost for short time,
they only contribute

00:53:48.284 --> 00:53:49.950
with this small
parameter to the result.

00:53:52.470 --> 00:53:56.950
So in other words,
this means after-- we

00:53:56.950 --> 00:53:59.750
have an interaction between
the environment and the system.

00:53:59.750 --> 00:54:01.690
We write it down
in second order,

00:54:01.690 --> 00:54:07.080
but the second
order result is now

00:54:07.080 --> 00:54:11.810
we evaluated by
factorizing the density

00:54:11.810 --> 00:54:17.180
matrix into our system
in the reservoir.

00:54:17.180 --> 00:54:19.810
So that means in that sense
if you factorize something,

00:54:19.810 --> 00:54:21.550
it looks as if it's
not interacting,

00:54:21.550 --> 00:54:23.050
but the trick is the same.

00:54:23.050 --> 00:54:25.870
You write down something
to first and second order,

00:54:25.870 --> 00:54:29.190
and once you have factored
out the important physics,

00:54:29.190 --> 00:54:31.820
now you can evaluate
the expression

00:54:31.820 --> 00:54:36.760
by using an approximation,
which is now the approximation

00:54:36.760 --> 00:54:38.910
that the density
matrix factorizes.

00:54:51.850 --> 00:55:00.430
So with that, this
is the approximation

00:55:00.430 --> 00:55:05.080
that we have made that the
correlation time is very short.

00:55:05.080 --> 00:55:09.170
And now we have a
differential equation

00:55:09.170 --> 00:55:11.870
for the density matrix
sigma, which describes

00:55:11.870 --> 00:55:12.960
or atomic system.

00:55:18.612 --> 00:55:21.170
We have traced out the
degrees of the reservoir.

00:55:24.120 --> 00:55:28.900
And now we want to insert B.17.

00:55:28.900 --> 00:55:31.000
You probably don't
remember what B.17 is.

00:55:31.000 --> 00:55:32.950
It says that the
interaction operator

00:55:32.950 --> 00:55:36.940
is a product of a, the
operator a for the atoms

00:55:36.940 --> 00:55:40.130
and r for the reservoir.

00:55:40.130 --> 00:55:44.280
So the reservoir part, tau
prime tau double prime,

00:55:44.280 --> 00:55:46.340
gives a correlation function.

00:55:46.340 --> 00:55:49.690
This is the correlation
function between the operator,

00:55:49.690 --> 00:55:54.290
r, at two different
times and the part

00:55:54.290 --> 00:55:59.009
which acts on our system, the a
part, is explicitly kept here.

00:56:03.320 --> 00:56:07.510
So this is now a
general master equation.

00:56:07.510 --> 00:56:10.200
It tells us the time
evolution of the density

00:56:10.200 --> 00:56:16.270
matrix in this form.

00:56:16.270 --> 00:56:18.370
It looks very
complicated, but this

00:56:18.370 --> 00:56:20.990
is because it's very general.

00:56:20.990 --> 00:56:31.600
In order to bring it
into an easier form,

00:56:31.600 --> 00:56:38.590
we want to now introduce a basis
of states, energy eigenstates

00:56:38.590 --> 00:56:41.960
of the unperturbed
system, and write down

00:56:41.960 --> 00:56:45.920
all of these operator into
such a basis of states.

00:56:48.960 --> 00:56:53.080
But anyway you saw here how
we had an exact equation,

00:56:53.080 --> 00:56:57.120
and the main
approximation we made

00:56:57.120 --> 00:57:01.680
is that the operator
acting on the environment

00:57:01.680 --> 00:57:03.460
has a very short
correlation time.

00:57:07.907 --> 00:57:08.490
Any questions?

00:57:11.676 --> 00:57:13.850
Well, you're only
a few minutes away

00:57:13.850 --> 00:57:17.040
from producing this result
to Fermi's golden rule, which

00:57:17.040 --> 00:57:18.810
you have known for
a long, long time.

00:57:18.810 --> 00:57:21.350
It's just we have made
very general assumptions.

00:57:21.350 --> 00:57:25.770
You see sort of how the
assumptions propagate,

00:57:25.770 --> 00:57:31.730
but now if you write it down
for an energy eigenbasis,

00:57:31.730 --> 00:57:35.550
you will immediately see
results you have probably

00:57:35.550 --> 00:57:39.310
known since your childhood.

00:57:39.310 --> 00:57:41.330
So we want to have
energy eigenstates

00:57:41.330 --> 00:57:42.940
of the atomic
operators, so this is

00:57:42.940 --> 00:57:44.650
sort of ground and
excited state if you

00:57:44.650 --> 00:57:48.060
think about a two-level system.

00:57:48.060 --> 00:57:53.100
The previous equation,
I have to go back to it.

00:58:00.520 --> 00:58:04.130
Our previous equation is
a differential equation

00:58:04.130 --> 00:58:08.730
for the density matrix here,
and here is the density matrix.

00:58:08.730 --> 00:58:12.340
So now we formulate
this equation

00:58:12.340 --> 00:58:16.230
into an energy eigenbasis,
and what do we get?

00:58:16.230 --> 00:58:18.850
Well, we get an equation
for the matrix elements,

00:58:18.850 --> 00:58:21.290
and what matrix
elements are important?

00:58:21.290 --> 00:58:24.160
diagonal matrix elements
which are population

00:58:24.160 --> 00:58:26.870
of diagonal matrix elements
which are coherences.

00:58:26.870 --> 00:58:29.190
So we pretty much
take this equation,

00:58:29.190 --> 00:58:31.800
use the energy
eigenbasis and look,

00:58:31.800 --> 00:58:34.327
what do we get for
the populations

00:58:34.327 --> 00:58:35.910
and what do we get
for the coherences.

00:58:50.450 --> 00:58:57.140
So the structure is
now the following.

00:58:57.140 --> 00:58:59.860
That we have our
matrix elements ab.

00:59:03.780 --> 00:59:09.030
There is one part which looks
like a unitary time evolution.

00:59:09.030 --> 00:59:11.180
This is what comes from
the Hamilton operator.

00:59:11.180 --> 00:59:15.420
This is sort of the-- we'll
see that in a moment--

00:59:15.420 --> 00:59:19.020
but this is the time
evolution without relaxation

00:59:19.020 --> 00:59:21.330
and now we have
something here which

00:59:21.330 --> 00:59:24.650
are generalized
relaxation coefficients.

00:59:24.650 --> 00:59:26.960
And you will find if
you go further above

00:59:26.960 --> 00:59:29.450
that those relaxation
coefficients are directly

00:59:29.450 --> 00:59:34.440
related to the correlation
function of the reservoir.

00:59:34.440 --> 00:59:42.260
So we can now specify what
happens between populations.

00:59:42.260 --> 00:59:45.580
Population means that we
have a differential equation,

00:59:45.580 --> 00:59:48.770
let's say between
sigma aa the puller,

00:59:48.770 --> 01:00:01.410
and sigma cc, so we
have a rate coefficient

01:00:01.410 --> 01:00:04.900
which connects the
population in state A

01:00:04.900 --> 01:00:10.370
with the population in state C.

01:00:10.370 --> 01:00:14.910
And if you take this expression,
you find several things.

01:00:14.910 --> 01:00:18.180
Well, you find
Fermi's golden rule,

01:00:18.180 --> 01:00:21.510
in a generalized
way-- that's always

01:00:21.510 --> 01:00:25.590
nice-- you find
Fermi's golden rule.

01:00:25.590 --> 01:00:29.530
When you integrate over time,
you often get data function,

01:00:29.530 --> 01:00:32.200
and you expect to get a
delta function because

01:00:32.200 --> 01:00:34.040
of energy conservation.

01:00:34.040 --> 01:00:36.710
So you get that, of
course, naturally.

01:00:36.710 --> 01:00:42.040
Secondly, we have second
order matrix element,

01:00:42.040 --> 01:00:44.920
which you know from
Fermi's golden rule,

01:00:44.920 --> 01:00:47.710
but now we have the
following situation

01:00:47.710 --> 01:00:51.770
that the matrix element
in Fermi's golden rule

01:00:51.770 --> 01:00:57.190
may actually depend on the
state, mu, of the environment.

01:00:57.190 --> 01:00:59.360
So you have maybe 10
different possibilities

01:00:59.360 --> 01:01:01.550
for the environment,
and Fermi's golden rule

01:01:01.550 --> 01:01:03.610
gives you spontaneous
emission, which

01:01:03.610 --> 01:01:05.810
is different for
those 10 states.

01:01:05.810 --> 01:01:08.940
And naturally, since we have
performed the partial trace

01:01:08.940 --> 01:01:12.000
over the environment,
we have all those rates

01:01:12.000 --> 01:01:14.460
weighted with the probability
that the environment

01:01:14.460 --> 01:01:16.850
is in one of those states.

01:01:16.850 --> 01:01:20.560
So what you find here is
a simple generalization

01:01:20.560 --> 01:01:21.950
of Fermi's golden rule.

01:01:26.330 --> 01:01:36.980
And if you look at the
off-diagonal matrix elements,

01:01:36.980 --> 01:01:39.260
for instance, you
want to know what

01:01:39.260 --> 01:01:44.540
is this rate, what is the rate
coefficient, which gives you

01:01:44.540 --> 01:01:48.130
the time derivative
of the coherence,

01:01:48.130 --> 01:01:51.360
and it's multiplied
with the coherence.

01:01:51.360 --> 01:01:56.640
You'll find now that in general,
this rate coefficient has

01:01:56.640 --> 01:02:01.640
a damping term, but it may
also have an imaginary term.

01:02:01.640 --> 01:02:05.320
And I hope you remember when we
played with diagrams, that we

01:02:05.320 --> 01:02:07.040
had something similar.

01:02:07.040 --> 01:02:11.300
There was something which we
called the radiative shift.

01:02:11.300 --> 01:02:14.800
I called it the AC stock
effect of a single photon,

01:02:14.800 --> 01:02:17.170
and here it is a
level shift which

01:02:17.170 --> 01:02:19.940
comes because the environment
interacts with your system

01:02:19.940 --> 01:02:21.960
and it shifts the
levels a little bit.

01:02:21.960 --> 01:02:23.940
So in addition to
just relaxation,

01:02:23.940 --> 01:02:25.950
spontaneous emission,
and damping,

01:02:25.950 --> 01:02:29.940
there is also a dispersive
part, a level shift,

01:02:29.940 --> 01:02:35.950
and it has exactly
the same structure.

01:02:35.950 --> 01:02:40.240
Let me add that delta
ab is the difference

01:02:40.240 --> 01:02:46.470
between the shift of state
b and the shift of state a.

01:02:46.470 --> 01:02:51.100
And those shifts have
exactly the same structure.

01:02:51.100 --> 01:02:55.010
You have to take the principle
part of something which

01:02:55.010 --> 01:02:58.070
has 1 over the
difference of energies,

01:02:58.070 --> 01:03:02.390
and we discussed that
this has to be understood

01:03:02.390 --> 01:03:07.930
by somewhere adding an
infinitesimal imaginary part

01:03:07.930 --> 01:03:10.120
and doing the right thing
with complex function.

01:03:10.120 --> 01:03:13.360
It's actually related to
Laplace time difference

01:03:13.360 --> 01:03:17.590
between Laplace transformation
and Fourier transformation.

01:03:17.590 --> 01:03:21.110
So anyway what I find
sort of beautiful

01:03:21.110 --> 01:03:23.780
is that we started with
a most general situation.

01:03:23.780 --> 01:03:25.400
We perform the partial trace.

01:03:25.400 --> 01:03:28.190
We made one assumption of
short correlation times,

01:03:28.190 --> 01:03:31.880
and a lot of things we have
known about quantum system

01:03:31.880 --> 01:03:34.310
just pops out in a
very general form here.

01:03:37.060 --> 01:03:39.130
Any questions about so far?

01:03:49.280 --> 01:03:55.160
Well, the coherences are,
of course, more interesting

01:03:55.160 --> 01:03:56.140
than the population.

01:03:56.140 --> 01:03:59.780
Coherence is always something
physicists get excited about it

01:03:59.780 --> 01:04:03.000
because it captures
something which goes often

01:04:03.000 --> 01:04:08.200
beyond classical
system that we have

01:04:08.200 --> 01:04:10.170
quantum mechanical coherences.

01:04:10.170 --> 01:04:14.610
And what happens is the
coefficient here, which

01:04:14.610 --> 01:04:18.700
provides the damping
of the coherence,

01:04:18.700 --> 01:04:22.460
just comes out of the
formalism, has two parts.

01:04:22.460 --> 01:04:34.040
And one part is
an adiabatic part

01:04:34.040 --> 01:04:38.090
and the other one is
a non-adiabatic part.

01:04:38.090 --> 01:04:39.940
Well, and that makes sense.

01:04:39.940 --> 01:04:42.710
If you have two quantum
states and there

01:04:42.710 --> 01:04:45.886
is a coherence, some
phase between the two,

01:04:45.886 --> 01:04:49.750
the phase can get lost if you
do a transition between the two

01:04:49.750 --> 01:04:53.890
states or one state undergoes
a collision and is quenched.

01:04:53.890 --> 01:04:58.480
So you definitely have one
part which is due to the fact

01:04:58.480 --> 01:05:03.760
that the quantum states
or the population

01:05:03.760 --> 01:05:08.660
changes, and you find that there
is this state-changing part,

01:05:08.660 --> 01:05:11.760
which is pretty much
the sum of all the rate

01:05:11.760 --> 01:05:14.030
coefficient leading
out of state,

01:05:14.030 --> 01:05:16.310
leading to the decay
of state a and leading

01:05:16.310 --> 01:05:18.810
to the decay of state b.

01:05:18.810 --> 01:05:21.560
In other words, if you have
a two-level system, which

01:05:21.560 --> 01:05:29.510
has a coherence and you
have decay of the excited

01:05:29.510 --> 01:05:31.640
state and decay of
the ground state,

01:05:31.640 --> 01:05:36.430
you would expect that those
decay terms appear also

01:05:36.430 --> 01:05:39.950
in the decay of the coherence
between the two levels

01:05:39.950 --> 01:05:46.070
and they do, and they appear
with the correct factor of 1/2.

01:05:46.070 --> 01:05:49.580
But there is another possibility
and this is the following.

01:05:49.580 --> 01:05:54.540
You can have no [INAUDIBLE] of
the population of the state,

01:05:54.540 --> 01:05:57.450
but you can still
lose the coherence.

01:05:57.450 --> 01:05:59.360
The model you
should maybe make is

01:05:59.360 --> 01:06:01.500
that you have spin
up, spin down.

01:06:01.500 --> 01:06:03.920
You are not perturbing
the populations

01:06:03.920 --> 01:06:06.650
in spin up and spin
down, but the environment

01:06:06.650 --> 01:06:09.930
provides fluctuating
magnetic field.

01:06:09.930 --> 01:06:13.680
Then due to the
fluctuating magnetic field,

01:06:13.680 --> 01:06:16.240
you no longer can keep
track of the phase,

01:06:16.240 --> 01:06:18.430
and that means in
your identity matrix

01:06:18.430 --> 01:06:21.150
the off-diagonal
matrix elements decay.

01:06:21.150 --> 01:06:25.670
And we find that here this
is the second part which

01:06:25.670 --> 01:06:28.840
in this book is called
the adiabatic part,

01:06:28.840 --> 01:06:32.090
and the physics behind it
is now pure de-phasing.

01:06:35.210 --> 01:06:37.880
So it's an independent
way for coherences

01:06:37.880 --> 01:06:42.275
to decay independent of the
decay of the population.

01:06:56.374 --> 01:06:56.873
Questions?

