and its Hermitian conjugate
sigma plus, all of this

01:16:23.920 --> 01:16:28.330
have to appear in
this combination.

01:16:28.330 --> 01:16:28.830
Yes, Collin.

01:16:28.830 --> 01:16:31.716
AUDIENCE: This is still
in my interaction picture.

01:16:31.716 --> 01:16:32.216
Right?

01:16:32.216 --> 01:16:34.696
There's no dynamical
phase evolution

01:16:34.696 --> 01:16:38.144
that we put back in there.

01:16:38.144 --> 01:16:38.810
PROFESSOR: Yeah.

01:16:38.810 --> 01:16:39.570
OK.

01:16:39.570 --> 01:16:43.460
What we do in general if the
system is driven by a laser

01:16:43.460 --> 01:16:46.230
beam, for instance,
Rabi oscillation,

01:16:46.230 --> 01:16:49.460
we simply add up the dynamics
of the Rabi oscillation

01:16:49.460 --> 01:16:54.294
of the unitary time evolution
to the time evolution

01:16:54.294 --> 01:16:55.210
done by the reservoir.

01:16:55.210 --> 01:16:58.654
AUDIENCE: So this form is always
in the interaction picture?

01:16:58.654 --> 01:17:00.340
PROFESSOR: Well, this
is, you would say,

01:17:00.340 --> 01:17:04.540
this form is what is
the relaxation provided

01:17:04.540 --> 01:17:05.890
by the environment.

01:17:05.890 --> 01:17:07.980
And if you drive the
system in addition

01:17:07.980 --> 01:17:11.450
with the coherent field,
unitary time evolution,

01:17:11.450 --> 01:17:15.250
you would add it to it.

01:17:15.250 --> 01:17:17.970
So in other words,
what I'm telling

01:17:17.970 --> 01:17:21.340
you here is that this is
the general structure,

01:17:21.340 --> 01:17:23.400
and if you have a
system which interacts

01:17:23.400 --> 01:17:26.180
with an environment in
five different ways,

01:17:26.180 --> 01:17:29.090
with a dipole wand, with a
magnetic moment and such,

01:17:29.090 --> 01:17:32.320
you have maybe five
interaction terms

01:17:32.320 --> 01:17:35.920
and then you have to perform
the sum over five operators,

01:17:35.920 --> 01:17:39.150
and here one of them is
a sigma minus operator.

01:17:39.150 --> 01:17:42.410
So in other words,
if you want to know

01:17:42.410 --> 01:17:46.550
what is the whole world of
possibilities for quantum

01:17:46.550 --> 01:17:49.950
system to relax and dissipate
with an environment,

01:17:49.950 --> 01:17:52.610
you can pretty much
take any operator which

01:17:52.610 --> 01:17:55.990
acts on your system,
but then put it

01:17:55.990 --> 01:17:59.060
into this so-called
Lindblad form

01:17:59.060 --> 01:18:01.380
and you have a
possible environment.

01:18:04.560 --> 01:18:07.410
And I mentioned
I think last week

01:18:07.410 --> 01:18:11.060
that people are now in
our field actively working

01:18:11.060 --> 01:18:13.260
on environmental engineering.

01:18:13.260 --> 01:18:16.870
They want to expose a system
to an artificial environment

01:18:16.870 --> 01:18:20.070
and hope the system is
not relaxing, let's say,

01:18:20.070 --> 01:18:23.690
to a broken ground state, but
to a fancy correlated state.

01:18:27.500 --> 01:18:32.160
So what this Lindblad form,
if the operators appears

01:18:32.160 --> 01:18:37.770
in this way, what it
insures is the following.

01:18:37.770 --> 01:18:40.800
Just imagine if we
have an equation,

01:18:40.800 --> 01:18:43.020
a derivative of
the density matrix,

01:18:43.020 --> 01:18:45.310
which depends on
the density matrix,

01:18:45.310 --> 01:18:48.080
you could write down a
differential equation and say

01:18:48.080 --> 01:18:49.430
is it possible?

01:18:49.430 --> 01:18:52.240
Well, it has to be consistent
with quantum physics.

01:18:52.240 --> 01:18:53.980
You have certain requirements.

01:18:53.980 --> 01:18:58.660
One requirement is that
rho, the density matrix,

01:18:58.660 --> 01:19:01.870
always has to be
the density matrix.

01:19:01.870 --> 01:19:04.270
The trace equal 1
has to be conserved.

01:19:04.270 --> 01:19:09.190
A density matrix always must
have non-negative eigenvalues,

01:19:09.190 --> 01:19:10.740
otherwise, what
you write down, it

01:19:10.740 --> 01:19:13.200
might be a nice differential
equation, but quantum

01:19:13.200 --> 01:19:15.290
mechanically, it's nonsense.

01:19:15.290 --> 01:19:20.940
But now there is one more
thing, which is also necessary.

01:19:20.940 --> 01:19:26.380
This time evolution of the
system's density matrix

01:19:26.380 --> 01:19:31.370
must come from a unitary time
evolution of a bigger system.

01:19:31.370 --> 01:19:35.190
So you must be able to extend
your system into a bigger

01:19:35.190 --> 01:19:36.890
system, which is
now the environment,

01:19:36.890 --> 01:19:40.710
and this whole system must
follow a Schrodinger equation

01:19:40.710 --> 01:19:43.760
with a Hamilton as a
unitary time evolution.

01:19:43.760 --> 01:19:46.030
And this is where
it's restrictive.

01:19:46.030 --> 01:19:49.050
You cannot just write down a
differential equation and hope

01:19:49.050 --> 01:19:51.140
that this will fill
some requirement,

01:19:51.140 --> 01:19:56.350
and what people have shown is
under very general assumptions,

01:19:56.350 --> 01:20:01.320
it is the Lindblad form
which allows for it.

01:20:01.320 --> 01:20:05.360
So some operator always
has to appear in this form.

01:20:08.120 --> 01:20:13.310
So often in this
Lindblad form, you

01:20:13.310 --> 01:20:18.070
have an operator, which is
called a jump operator, which

01:20:18.070 --> 01:20:20.390
is responsible for
the measurement, which

01:20:20.390 --> 01:20:22.610
the environment
does on your system.

01:20:22.610 --> 01:20:24.820
The jump operator is
here, the operator

01:20:24.820 --> 01:20:28.740
which takes the atom from the
excited to the ground state.

01:20:28.740 --> 01:20:32.480
With that you need a photon,
and the photon can be measured.

01:20:32.480 --> 01:20:37.910
So often you can describe a
system by a jump operator,

01:20:37.910 --> 01:20:41.130
and if the jump operator is
put into this Lindblad form,

01:20:41.130 --> 01:20:49.760
then you have a valid master
equation for your system.

01:20:52.270 --> 01:20:53.610
So let me wrap up.

01:21:05.924 --> 01:21:10.320
If you take now the definition
of the raising and lowering

01:21:10.320 --> 01:21:14.540
operator, and you take the
form I showed you, the Lindblad

01:21:14.540 --> 01:21:21.052
form, you'll find now
this differential equation

01:21:21.052 --> 01:21:22.135
for your two-level system.

01:21:24.900 --> 01:21:27.930
And this is one part of
the Optical Bloch Equation.

01:21:27.930 --> 01:21:30.420
Now, coming to
Collin's question,

01:21:30.420 --> 01:21:32.280
if you include
the time evolution

01:21:32.280 --> 01:21:35.600
of the classical field,
this is a coherent evolution

01:21:35.600 --> 01:21:37.610
of the Bloch vector,
which I showed

01:21:37.610 --> 01:21:39.790
at the beginning of
the class, and we

01:21:39.790 --> 01:21:44.620
add this and what I wrote down
at the beginning of the class.

01:21:44.620 --> 01:21:48.792
Then we find the famous
Optical Bloch Equations

01:21:48.792 --> 01:21:50.000
in the Jaynes-Cummings model.

01:21:55.610 --> 01:22:00.730
So these are now the
Optical Bloch Equations,

01:22:00.730 --> 01:22:03.760
and I hope you enjoy now after
this complicated discussion,

01:22:03.760 --> 01:22:04.910
how simple they are.

01:22:04.910 --> 01:22:07.700
And it is this simple
set of equations,

01:22:07.700 --> 01:22:10.650
which will be used in
the rest of the course

01:22:10.650 --> 01:22:13.480
to describe the time
evolution of the system.

01:22:20.430 --> 01:22:22.630
Just because I did
some generalizations

01:22:22.630 --> 01:22:26.020
about the Lindblad equation,
I copied that into the lecture

01:22:26.020 --> 01:22:29.230
notes from Wikipedia,
and probably now you

01:22:29.230 --> 01:22:33.680
sort of understand what is the
most general Lindblad equation.

01:22:33.680 --> 01:22:36.760
It has a Hamiltonian
part and then it

01:22:36.760 --> 01:22:41.070
has jump operators like
you sigma minus operator,

01:22:41.070 --> 01:22:45.100
but it has to come in
the form that the jump

01:22:45.100 --> 01:22:49.130
operator and its complex
conjugate, emission. conjugate,

01:22:49.130 --> 01:22:53.310
is on the left side, on the
right side, and left and right

01:22:53.310 --> 01:22:55.130
of your density matrix.

01:22:55.130 --> 01:22:57.210
So this is the generalization
I've mentioned.

01:23:02.980 --> 01:23:05.720
Yeah. with that I think with
that we've derived the master

